IPL Dataset

Description

The ipl_batsmen_data provides data on 70 players from the 2019 edition of the IPL. The dataset provides observations on 7 variables and also contains the cost of each of the players.

Objective & Approach

The objective is to analyse the data provided and arrive at an objective classification of players based on their performances. The analyst seeks to identify good value acquisitions across the categories. The K-Means Clustering Analysis will be employed to classify players into clusters. The analyst acknowledges that the data contains players who may have been acquired for skills other that batmanship. The current analysis is restricted only their performances in batting.

K-Means Clustering Analysis

Normalising the data points to be used in the analysis

n_df <- scale(df[ , 3:9])

Determining the ideal number of clusters using the Elbow, Silhouette, Gap Statistic Methods

elbow_plot <- fviz_nbclust(n_df, kmeans, method = "wss")
elbow_plot

silhouette_plot <- fviz_nbclust(n_df, kmeans, method = "silhouette")
silhouette_plot

gap_stat <- fviz_nbclust(n_df, kmeans, method = "gap_stat")
gap_stat

Both the Elbow and Gap Statistic methods indicate 4 as the ideal number of clusters for the current analysis.

K-Means Analysis

set.seed(2703)

kmeans_4cl <- kmeans(n_df, 4, nstart = 25)
kmeans_4cl

Analysis of Resultant Clusters

Cluster Classification

The ranking of clusters was found to be 2, 1, 3, 4. The same shall be now classified as : 2 = Excellent, 1 = Good, 3 = Average Acquisition, 4 = Underperforming

df$classification <- ifelse(df$cluster == 2, "Excellent", 
                            ifelse(df$cluster == 1, "Good", 
                                   if_else(df$cluster == 3, "Average", "Underperforming")))

df$classification <- factor(df$classification, levels = c("Excellent", "Good", "Average", 
                            "Underperforming"), ordered = T)

levels(df$classification)
## [1] "Excellent"       "Good"            "Average"         "Underperforming"

Conclusion

sub_df %>% group_by(classification) %>% summarise(Avg_Salary = round(mean(Salary), digits = 2), 
                                                  Total_Runs = sum(Runs), 
                                                  Avg_of_Avgs = mean(Avg), 
                                                  Avg_Sr = mean(SR))
## # A tibble: 4  5
##   classification  Avg_Salary Total_Runs Avg_of_Avgs Avg_Sr
##   <ord>                <dbl>      <dbl>       <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 Excellent             1.42       2929        46.5   144.
## 2 Good                  1.63       2748        51.2   167.
## 3 Average               0.87       7630        31.7   135.
## 4 Underperforming       0.74       4141        20.2   125.

The analysis was able to identify 2 groups of high performing player along with par and under-performers. With the average spend for the top 2 classes being double the other 2, Teams would be advised to identify bargain pick ups like Jonny Bairstow (Sunrisers Hyderabad) and Chris Gayle (Kings XI). Cluster 3 (Average) reveals multiple marquee players (Rohit Sharma, Steve Smith, Suresh Raina) that have been picked up at premium prices but have delivered underwhelming results. As per the present analysis, it would be prudent for teams to limits premium player to one or two and leave enough payroll space to increase their share in the average group.
